       <article class="node node-page clearfix" id="node-145">
        <div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden">
         <div class="field-items">
          <div class="field-item even">
           <h2>
            News &amp; Updates
           </h2>
           <hr/>
           <h3>
            UPCOMING Legal affairs TRAINING SESSIONS
           </h3>
           <div>
            <h4>
             <span>
              Campus Response to Student Behavioral Concerns: Three Levels of Care
             </span>
            </h4>
            <div>
             When: Thursday, March 21 from 10-11:15 am
            </div>
            <div>
             Where: Cone 113
            </div>
            <div>
             <em>
              Who: Expert panelists include
              <strong>
               Jeff Baker,
              </strong>
              Police and Public Safety;
              <strong>
               Christine Reed Davis
              </strong>
              , Dean of Students Office;
              <strong>
               Larry Gourdine
              </strong>
              , Student Assistance and Support Services;
              <strong>
               Jesh Humphrey
              </strong>
              , Institutional Integrity; and
              <strong>
               David Spano
              </strong>
              , Counseling and Psychological Services.
             </em>
            </div>
            <div>
            </div>
            <div>
             <span>
              UNC Charlotte faculty and staff occasionally confront or learn about student behaviors that are troubling, disruptive, or even threatening. This session will outline the cross-divisional approaches taken by the university to assess and address concerning student behaviors through three levels of interconnected care: the Niner Care Team, the Campus Behavioral Intervention Team, and the Threat Assessment Team.  Presenters will discuss how to report concerning behaviors to the university, how those reports are managed, the resources utilized to assess risks and provide student support, as well as the laws, policies, and other considerations that govern how information about student behavior is conveyed to the university community.
             </span>
            </div>
            <div>
            </div>
            <div dir="ltr">
             <div dir="ltr">
              <div dir="ltr">
               <p>
                ​For more information about past training sessions and to learn about upcoming training sessions, see the
                <a href="/legal-services/legal-affairs-training-sessions">
                 Legal Affairs Training Sessions page
                </a>
                .​
               </p>
               <hr/>
               <h3>
                OLa attorneys co-author paper on emotional support animals
               </h3>
               <p>
                Associate Vice Chancellor and Deputy General Counsel Sam Sears and Legal Fellow Kris Caudle have have co-authored a nationally-distributed article entitled "Emotional Support Animals in Higher Education: Challenging Scenarios and Proposed Solutions." (Copyright 2019 by Jeffrey J. Nolan, J.D., Samantha Sears, J.D., Kristopher Caudle, J.D.) The NACUANOTE article is a publication of the National Association of College and University Attorneys (NACUA). A copy of the article is available to University employees upon request
               </p>
              </div>
             </div>
            </div>
           </div>
